  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Benin programme 2017</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">1. Political update 2017 
Benin continues to enjoy a stable democratic regime. The presidential elections of March 2016 recorded a high number of candidates, of the 36 a large number were businessmen. The election took place in a peaceful climate and resulted in the victory of Patrice Talon Athanasius William, a multimillionaire businessman who made his fortune in the cotton sector.
In April of this year, the Talon administration announced its intention to initiate profound structural reforms which has since dominated the political news cycle. To do this, it established a political and institutional reform commission. The results of the work of this commission to revise the constitution were shared with the government recently, however the public are awaiting for the recommendations and results to be published. The reforms are expected to go to referendum after a vote in the national assembly. 
In the national assembly parties are yet to confirm their allegiance with the new government or announce their opposition and for this reason the parliamentary minority and majority are still unclear.

2. Programme &amp; Theory of Change Update
The main problem analysis in the ToC focusses on a lack of mutual trust, little political ambition, a deeply conservative political culture and a number of technical mismatches between the legislative system and the political system that prevents democratic transformation. In 2015 and 2016 a new speaker of parliament and president both vocal about democratic reform offers a window of opportunity to address some of the democratic deficits holding the countries reforms back such as a constitutional reform.
In this sense the ToC is still very relevant to the political context. This translate into a programme that specifically aims to improve trust among youthful political stakeholders and thereby influencing the political culture, at the same time the programme is working towards interparty dialogue by supporting interparty activities to address political reform.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="3">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Political actors are defined as the combined main target group of the Strategic Partnership: - (representatives of) political parties - politicians - (Members of) Parliament and its Committees - Other elected representatives at local levels. NIMD will primarily focus on political parties.</narrative>
  </description>
